+# ClaimGate / Codex Ratchet / Lev Cognitive Wavegraph Overgoal
+
+Short `/goal` version:
+
+```text
+Build the Lev-native ClaimGate cognitive wavegraph patch: a structured nested-wave/council runtime where durable agents are skill/MMM/source-loaded members, waves and councils can loop with OxRicker-style verify/reject/requeue gates, management sidecars route resources/laggards/failures/receipts, Codex Ratchet digs axioms/constraints/gates/attractor basins, and outputs become proposal-only Lev graph patches with host receipts instead of a side proof system.
+```
+
+## What We Are Actually Making
+
+This is not just a narrow Gate 0/Gate 0A patch.
+
+The real object is a **Lev-native cognitive wavegraph patch**:
+
+```text
+source packs + skill packs + MMMs
+  -> durable cognitive members
+  -> councils and subcouncils
+  -> sequenced waves
+  -> wave loops and gate loops
+  -> failure packets and repair/requeue routing
+  -> axiom / constraint / gate / attractor-basin digging
+  -> proposal-only graph patches
+  -> host Lev admission receipts
+```
+
+The point is to make Lev able to run structured high-leverage knowledge work:
+
+- not random swarms
+- not flat one-shot councils
+- not Wizard branding theater
+- not a second proof system next to Lev
+- not a pile of model outputs
+
+It is a patch that lets Lev use ClaimGate / Codex Ratchet / Wizard-style work as a **disciplined project-harness cognition layer**.
+
+The first tangible surface is not another freeform architecture note. It must
+be a Lev execution contract / workflow spec with a tiny fixture, deterministic
+validator, and receipt trail:
+
+```text
+FlowMind / execution-contract shaped spec
+  -> bounded Tick
+  -> nested wave fixture
+  -> gate-loop fixture
+  -> host-readable receipts
+  -> proposal-only graph patch packet
+```
+
+## Core Runtime Shape
+
+### 1. Cognitive Members Are Real Objects
+
+Every agent, council member, subcouncil, durable team, and management sidecar must have a manifest:
+
+- role
+- allowed authority
+- MMM / vernacular refs
+- skill refs
+- source refs
+- model lane policy
+- input contract
+- output contract
+- gate contract
+- requeue policy
+- receipt target
+
+Then the runtime must actually load those refs into context and hash what was loaded.
+
+Declared skills are not enough. A member is not valid until its skills/MMMs/sources are loaded and receipted.
+
+### 2. Waves Are Not Councils
+
+A wave is a phase of work.
+
+A council is a structured deliberation/production group inside a wave.
+
+A council can contain:
+
+- agents
+- durable teams
+- subcouncils
+- model lanes
+- skill-specific lanes
+- source-specific lanes
+
+Waves can:
+
+- run sequentially
+- fan out internally
+- contain councils that loop
+- loop back to earlier waves
+- be reopened by later gates
+- have management sidecars running in parallel
+
+This preserves the original Wizard intuition: wave 1 -> wave 2 -> wave 3 can itself become a loop, and each wave can contain internal loops.
+
+Wizard v4.3 is source material, not a prison. The patch may define new Lev-native
+wave types when the work requires them, as long as the wave/council/member
+topology is explicit, bounded, and receipted.
+
+### 3. Management Plane Runs Beside The Work Plane
+
+Management is not another hidden work council.
+
+Management sidecars watch and route:
+
+- context pressure
+- laggards
+- resource budget
+- model lane health
+- failed members
+- duplicate work
+- stalled branches
+- missing receipts
+- requeue targets
+- escalation / kill switches
+
+Management can route, throttle, quarantine, or request repair. It cannot silently mutate results or promote work.
+
+### 4. Model Lanes Are First-Class Audit Inputs
+
+The model plane is not optional flavor. It is part of Gate 0A formation for any
+run that claims council, swarm, multi-model, or external-audit diversity.
+
+Required lane families:
+
+- Claude Bridge bulk/controller lanes:
+  - many Sonnet / Sonnet-high-style controller workers for rubric, manifests,
+    repair hypotheses, receipt checks, and premortem scaffolding
+  - Opus for apex contradiction finding, architecture judgment, and final
+    high-stakes review
+  - Haiku only for cheap inventory/counting/scouting when useful
+- OpenRouter Chinese-family checks:
+  - `minimax/minimax-m3`
+  - `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro`
+  - `moonshotai/kimi-k2.7-code`
+  - `qwen/qwen3.7-plus`
+  - `qwen/qwen3.7-max`
+  - `z-ai/glm-5.2` as a guarded deep-audit/sparring lane with schema-repair
+    wrapper when strict JSON is required
+- xAI / Grok: outside-family critique lane with advisory-only authority.
+- Google Gemini TUI: explicit Google TUI lane. Generic Gemini API usage does
+  not satisfy the TUI lane. If unavailable, emit an unavailable receipt.
+- Codex/local: repo-grounded implementation, test, diff, and receipt lane.
+
+Every model lane must declare provider, model, family, purpose, prompt hash,
+disclosure policy, output schema, budget, receipt target, and
+`advisory_only` authority. Every outside lane must pass the data-export gate:
+private patch context stays local unless explicitly approved; redacted briefs
+are the default.
+
+Provider execution must enter through named adapter factories and the injected
+runner seam. Claude Bridge, OpenRouter Chinese-family models, xAI/Grok, Google
+Gemini TUI, and Codex/local routes may have different transports, but they all
+normalize into the same `ClaimGateModelLaneRuntimeOutcome` shape before Gate 0A
+aggregation. Timeout, schema-invalid output, provider error, blocked export,
+and unavailable route are receipted outcomes, not invisible absences. The
+factory layer is test-backed; live provider auth/tool invocation remains a
+separate availability/transport gate.
+
+Mass Claude Bridge spawning is allowed when useful, especially Sonnet
+controller fanout, but it must preserve per-lane receipts through aggregation.
+No aggregate can hide a failed lane, dropped dissent, missing schema, or
+unavailable provider.
+
+Model agreement is not proof. It is a signal that can trigger stricter
+verification, not faster promotion.
+
+### 5. Gate Loops Are OxRicker-Style Internal Loops
+
+Every gate has an internal loop:
+
+```text
+candidate output
+  -> verify every required item
+  -> reject failures
+  -> create FailurePacket
+  -> requeue only failed parts
+  -> rerun with changed contract/evidence/skill/model/route
+  -> stop only on gate clean, budget exhaustion, or circuit breaker
+```
+
+Each gate level is itself a loop. The whole gate ladder is also a loop.
+
+Passing a gate does not make it eternal. Later gates may reopen earlier gates, but only with:
+
+- prior gate receipt
+- later gate authority
+- contradiction artifact or stronger contract
+- downstream receipt invalidation rule
+- bounded reopen budget
+- circuit breaker
+
+### 6. Codex Ratchet Is The Deep Research Engine
+
+Codex Ratchet contributes the deeper math/science/research side:
+
+- attractor basin digging
+- axiom digging
+- constraint digging
+- gate digging
+- terrain/operator discipline
+- long-horizon project-state memory
+- falsifier and premortem pressure
+- proposal-only graph patches
+
+The end state is not "ClaimGate replaces Lev."
+
+The end state is: Lev evolves toward the same attractor basin because Lev is itself a project harness and ratchet.
+
+## Preservation And Source Discipline
+
+The work must stay patch-shaped and reviewable:
+
+- `.lev/pm/plans/` holds the live plan and goal reference.
+- `.lev/steering/runs/` holds model-lane, fixture, gate, and host-consumption receipts.
+- `docs/design/` holds stable bridge contracts that JP can review.
