+## Core Loop Model
+
+The system is not one loop. It is a ratchet of gates, and each gate has an internal loop.
+
+```text
+Gate Ratchet Loop
+  Gate N opens
+    -> internal candidate generation
+    -> multi-model lanes run only if allowed by data-export policy
+    -> per-model receipts preserved before aggregation
+    -> deterministic validator / structured evaluator
+    -> FailurePacket on reject
+    -> repair/reroute/requeue only failed parts
+    -> stop on gate clean, budget exhaustion, or circuit breaker
+  Gate N emits receipt
+  Gate N+1 may open
+  Later gates can reopen earlier gates with stronger contracts
+```
+
+This reconciles the two loop ideas:
+
+- Internal loops: each gate runs an OxRicker-style verify/reject/requeue process.
+- Cross-gate loops: passing a gate is provisional. Later evidence can reopen it. The full system can loop back from Gate 6 to Gate 1, or Gate 9 to Gate 3, without pretending earlier work is final.
+
+Reopening is not free-form. A reopen request must cite:
+
+- the earlier gate and receipt being reopened
+- the later gate that has authority to reopen it
+- a contradiction artifact or strictly stronger contract
+- a bounded reopen budget
+- a tick budget
+- the ceiling action when the budget expires
+
+Without those fields, reopening fails closed.
+
+No LLM, council, swarm, or branch can promote work. They can propose, score, criticize, and repair. Deterministic gates and host Lev receipts decide.
+
+A deterministic gate is a declared pass/fail/uncertain evaluator whose inputs, schema, evidence refs, claim ceiling, failure codes, and replay behavior are known before the gate runs. Human sign-off, LLM scoring, and model consensus can be evidence inputs only when the gate contract says how they are consumed.
+
